headline: US-based multinational companies will be exempt from global tax deal
summary: U.S. multinational corporations will be exempted from paying more corporate taxes overseas in a deal finalized by the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development.  The OECD announced Monday that nearly 150 countries have agreed on the plan, initially crafted in 2021, to stop large global companies from shifting profits to low-tax countries, no matter where they operate in the world.  The amended version excludes large U.S.-based multinational corporations from the 15% global minimum tax after negotiations between President Donald Trump's administration and other members of the Group of Seven wealthy nations.

headline: Emerging-Market Stocks Set for Record High Amid AI Optimism
summary: The MSCI Emerging Markets Index rose 1.2% as of 7:51 a.m. London time on Monday, set for a record close and also marking the best start to a year since 2018.  Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Co. accounted for more than half of the gauge’s gains after Goldman Sachs Group Inc. raised its price target for the supplier of Apple Inc. and Nivida Corp. Other major movers included Samsung Electronics, SK Hynix and Alibaba Group Holding Ltd.  The rally has been supported by a weaker dollar and US investors’ search for overseas assets, alongside reform momentum in economies from Ghana to South Korea.

Foxconn said revenue for the quarter grew significantly on both ⁠a quarter-on-quarter and year-on-year ‌basis, exceeding its expectations and creating a high base of comparison for the first quarter of 2026.

headline: This Vietnamese town boomed as factories left China. Now it’s asking what’s next?
summary: The transformation of Vietnam's Bac Ninh is evident in the signs above its shops and the spicy Chinese and Korean dishes on its tables.  Once known for its rice fields and the love duets of its centuries-old Quan Ho folk songs, the city just north of Hanoi has become one of Vietnam's busiest factory zones, reflecting a surge of investment, hastened by President Donald Trump’s tariff hikes, that are reshaping the region.  The economy has profited from friction between Washington and Beijing as factories shifted out of China, joining earlier waves of foreign investment by the Japanese and South Koreans that have made Vietnam a global manufacturing hub.

headline: Exclusive-Samsung to double mobile devices powered by Google's Gemini to 800 million units this year
summary: Samsung Electronics plans to double this year the number of its mobile devices with AI features powered by Google's Gemini, its co-CEO said, which would give the U.S. firm an edge over rivals as the global race in artificial ​intelligence hots up.  "We will apply AI to all products, all functions, and all services as quickly as possible," T M Roh ‌told Reuters in his first interview since becoming Samsung Electronics co-CEO in November.  The plan by the world's largest backer of Google's Android mobile platform is set to give a major boost to its developer Google, which is locked in a race with OpenAI and others to attract more consumer users to their AI model.
